bib_record.title: The production of positron emitters 75Br and 76Br: excitation functions and yields for 3He and alpha- particle induced nuclear reactions on arsenic

free_txt: Compact cyclotron 'CV28'
Errors are given in several points on the fig.
The errors in the energy scale were reduced by use of
relatively thin stacks and irradiating them with
varying incident particle energies. Thus, the errors in
the energy scale should not exceed 2 MeV in the most
unfavourable cases. Error decreases with increasing
energy. Value is given in several points on figs.
The total error in cross-sections were
obtained by summing up in quadrature the estimated
individual errors as described earlier(see
REL-REF: Probst+).
Compact cyclotron 'CV28'
The checks were also made
using Cu and Al monitor foils inserted in different
places of the stack.
Excitation functions were measured by the conventional
stacked foil technique (see REL-REF: R.Weinreich+).
Each target consisted of metallic arsenic suspended
in a self-supporting polystyrene film. The films were
prepared by pouring a suspension of as powder in a
benzene solution of polystyrene on a thin 'Al' sheet.
A stack consisted at maximum of 12 targets. The
amount of arsenic in each individual target was
determined after the completion of the experiment by
neutron activation analysis to be between 2.5 and
80 mg/cm2, that of polystyrene by weighing the target
and substracting the amount of arsenic.
/By authors/ Since most of the gamma-lines of 76Br
are the same as those in the decay of 76As, both
decaying to 76Se, and 76As is formed simultaneously
by the (3He,2p) and (alpha,2pn) reactions,
respectively, we had to use for 76Br the relatively
weak line of 1853 keV (14.0%) with lower detection
efficiency instead of the stronger ones 559 keV (72.4%)
and 657 keV (15.5%). The 1853 keV gamma-line, however,
is not emitted in the decay of 76As.
Measurement of the decay of 1853 keV shows a
half-life of 15.7 hr, a value comparable to the
accepted one of 16.0 hr. The 559 keV line shows a
longer half-life (e.g., 17.2 hr). 76As, however,
does not emit any strong gamma-line which is not
given out in the decay of 76Br. Using the 559 keV
alpha-line the total activity due to 76Br + 76As was
determined and the contribution of 76As was obtained
by subtraction (see REL-REF).

by the (alpha,2p) and of 56-hr 77Br by the (alpha,2n)
reaction no contribution of 77As to the measured
gamma-lines was considered since
(i) 77As decays to 97.5% into the ground state of 77Se
and so the gamma-yield is very low (see REL-REF) and
(ii) from the systematic trends it is to be expected
that the (alpha,2p) reaction should have a hundred-
fold lower yield than the (alpha,2n) reaction (see
REL-REF).
By the 3He activation of 75As no 77As is formed.
